Doyers Street

Early in the century, the bend in the street became known as “the Bloody Angle” because of numerous shootings among the Tong Gangs of Chinatown that lasted into the 1930s.  Hatchets were frequently used, leading to the creation of the expression, "hatchet man". In 1994, law enforcement officials said that more people died violently at the “Bloody Angle” than at any other street intersection in the United States.

My second book, titled Subjective Ideal, is now on sale at Amazon and CreateSpace! The book was designed by me and features 162 color pages of my NYC urban photography from the last 2 years.

If you enjoy this blog and my photography, please consider purchasing the book.  I receive royalties of $5.38 for each copy sold on Amazon and $11.38 from CreateSpace.  This money will help me buy new gear and keep the photos coming!  My first book, Urban Dreamscapes, is still for sale on Blurb; however, I’ve lowered the price to Blurb’s cost, so I no longer receive any royalties on sales.
